{{Distinguish|Alien Nation}}{{Multiple issues| {{Missing information|''Alien Nations''|date=November 2014}} {{Refimprove|date=November 2014}} }} {{Infobox video game |collapsible = |state = |title = Alien Nations |image = Alien Nations.jpg |caption = |developer = [[Neo Software]] |publisher = [[JoWooD Productions]] |series = |engine = |platforms = [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]], [[Mac OS]] |released = {{Dts|1999|5|11}} |genre = [[Real-time strategy]] |modes = |director = |producer = |designer = |programmer = |artist = |writer = |composer = [[Jesper Kyd]] |alt = }} '''''Alien Nations''''' ({{lang-de|Die Völker}}) is a [[PC game]] created by [[JoWooD Productions]] for [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]]-based computers published in 1999 and re-released on [[GOG.com]] in 2009. A sequel, ''The Nations'', was published in 2001. ''Alien Nations'' was a commercial hit in the German market, and ultimately sold close to 1 million units worldwide.
== Gameplay == {{Expand section|date=November 2014}} ''Alien Nations'' is a real-time strategy game for Windows based on building a nation and conquering others. The player may choose from 3 races – the Pimmons, the Amazons and the Sajkhi.
== Reception == ===Sales=== ''Alien Nations'' was a commercial hit in the German market. ''[[Der Spiegel]]''{{'}}s Frank Patalong noted that it was one of the [[construction and management simulation]]s that "dominated the German sales charts for years", alongside ''[[Anno 1602]]'' and the ''[[The Settlers|Settlers]]'' series.<ref name=spiegel>{{cite web | archiveurl=http://archive.is/brlik | url=http://www.spiegel.de/netzwelt/web/anno-1503-wuselige-zeitreise-a-220745.html | title=Wuselige Zeitreise | date=January 11, 2002| author=Patalong, Frank | work=[[Der Spiegel]] | archivedate=November 30, 2018 | deadurl=no | language=[[German language|German]] }}</ref> In German-speaking countries, it sold 150,000 units by June 2000. At the time, ''[[Der Standard]]'' reported that this made it "the best-selling computer game in the German-speaking world this year."<ref name=150k>{{cite web | url=https://derstandard.at/247922/Oesterreichische-Computerspiele-im-internationalen-Rampenlicht | title=Österreichische Computerspiele im internationalen Rampenlicht | date=June 8, 2000 | author=Isenegger, Peter | work=[[Der Standard]] | language=[[German language|German]] }}</ref> It was also a success in Russia, with sales of 80,000 units by April 2001.<ref name=80k>{{cite web | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181202032438/https://www.gamestar.de/artikel/jowood-in-russland,1336864.html| url=https://www.gamestar.de/artikel/jowood-in-russland,1336864.html | title=JoWood in Russland | author=''GameStar'' Editors | date=April 20, 2001 | archivedate=December 2, 2018 | work=[[GameStar]] | language=[[German language|German]] | deadurl=no }}</ref> ''Alien Nations'' ultimately sold "just under a million copies" by 2016, according to Micharl Furtenbach of [[Red Bull]].<ref name=redbull>{{cite web | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181202033039/https://www.redbull.com/at-de/games-aus-oesterreich-teil-1 | url=https://www.redbull.com/at-de/games-aus-oesterreich-teil-1 | title=Heimat bist du großer Spieleentwickler! (Teil 1) | author=Furtenbach, Micharl | date=January 18, 2016 | archivedate=December 2, 2018 | work=[[Red Bull]] | language=[[German language|German]] | deadurl=no }}</ref>
===Critical reviews=== Oleg Hazhinskiy of [[Game.EXE]] gave the game 4.1/5 and noted its strong similarities with ''[[The Settlers]]'' series. Among differences, he praised the marketing system, but also mentioned lacking combat.<ref>{{cite magazine |script-title=ru:Наследники по прямой |trans-title=Direct Heirs |url= |first=Олег |last=Хажинский |date=September 2001 |volume=9 |pages=58–59 |magazine=[[Game.EXE]] |publisher=Computerra |location=Moscow |language=Russian}}</ref>
